<text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
  <body>
    <div rend="parallel">
      <lg xml:id="MTA14">
<l>avaravar tāntā maṟintavā ṟētti</l>
<l>yivariva remperumā ṉeṉṟu – cuvarmicaic</l>
<l>cāttiyum vaittun toḻuva rulakaḷanta</l>
<l>mūrtti yuruvē mutal</l>
      </lg>
      <lg xml:lang="en">
<l>All of those people praising in ways known to each of them,</l>
<l>saying ‘this one [or] this one is our great lord,’ by painting on the wall</l>
<l>[and] keeping [an icon] they all worship the form that measured</l> 
<l>the world as the first of forms.<note xml:lang="en" place="foot">The direct object of toḻuvar line 4 employs the noun mūrtti – otherwise not used in the Antāti-s, except in Po. 76.2 where the pronominal derivation mūrttiyar refers to human beings – in apposition to the ubiquitous uru/uruvu/uruvam, possibly simply induced by etukai. </note></l>
      </lg>
    </div>
  </body>
